<div class="container">
    <div class="page_st">
        <div class="page">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-sm-12">
                <div class="main_heading  policies">
                    <h1>Policies</h1>
                    <div class="col-md-12 rules">
                        <h2 style="color:#106939;">LEAVE RULES </h2>
                        <strong>KINDS OF LEAVE:</strong>
                        <p>The following kinds of leave may be granted to employees:</p>
                        <ul style="list-style-type: decimal;">
                            <li>Casual leave (CL)</li>
                            <li>Special Casual leave (SCL)</li>
                            <li>Privilege/Earned leave (PL)</li>
                            <li>Medical/Sick leave (ML)</li>
                            <li>Maternity leave (MTL)</li>
                            <li>Paternity leave (OTL)</li>
                            <li>Extraordinary leave (EOL)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="col-md-12 rules">
                        
                            <br />
                           
                                <strong>1. CASUAL LEAVE (CL)</strong>
                                <ul style="list-style-type: square">
                                    <li>Casual leave may be granted up to a maximum of 15 days in a year, provided that no more than seven days be availed of at a time.  Casual leave may however be combined with or taken in continuation of Sunday’s or other authorized holidays, provided that the resulting period of absence from duty does not exceed 10 days in all.  Provided however that if an employee has been on duty during any year for less than 9 months, the Casual leave shall be reduced proportionately.  </li>
                                    <li>Casual leave shall lapse at the end of the year.</li>
                                    <li>It shall not be prefixed or suffixed to any other kind of leave except special casual leave.</li>
                                </ul>
                           
                            <br />
                           
                                <strong>2. SPECIAL CASUAL LEAVE (SCL)</strong>
                        <ul style="list-style-type: square">
                            <li>Special casual leave not exceeding seven days and not counting against ordinary casual leave may be granted.
                            </li>
</ul>
                        </ul>
                            <br />

                            <strong>3. PRIVILEGE/EARNED LEAVE (PL)</strong>
                            <ul style="list-style-type: square">
                                <li>A permanent employee shall be eligible for Earned Leave at the rate of one eleventh (1/11th) part of the duty.  </li>
                                <li>The maximum period of earned leave which an employee can accumulate is 270 days.  But no more than 120 days leave shall ordinarily be taken at a time, except for leave on preparatory retirement.</li>
                                <li>The intervening holidays shall be treated as leave.</li>
                            </ul>

                            <br />

                            <strong>4. MEDICAL/SICK LEAVE (ML)</strong>
                            <ul style="list-style-type: square">
                                <li>The employee shall be eligible for Sick Leave on full salary at the rate of 20 days for every year of service completed, subject to a maximum of 12 months during the employees’ entire period of service provided that where an employee has service exceeding 24 years, they shall be eligible for an additional sick leave at the rate of one month for each year of service in excess of 24 years, subject to a maximum of 3 (three) months. </li>
                            </ul>

                            <br />

                            <strong>5. MATERNITY LEAVE (MTL)</strong>
                            <ul style="list-style-type: square">
                                <li>Maternity leave, which shall be on substantive pay, shall be granted to a female employee for a period not exceeding 6 months on any one occasion and 12 months during the entire period of service. </li>
                            </ul>

                            <br />

                            <strong>6. PATERNITY LEAVE (PTL)</strong>
                            <ul style="list-style-type: square">
                                <li>Male employees with less than two surviving children shall be eligible for 15 days Paternity Leave during his wife’s confinement.  This leave may be combined with any other kind of leave except Casual Leave.  The leave may be availed upto 15 days before or upto 6 months from the date of delivery of the child.</li>
                            </ul>

                            <br />

                            <strong>7. EXTRA-ORDINARY LEAVE (EOL)</strong>
                            <ul style="list-style-type: square">
                                <li>Extra-ordinary leave may be granted to an employee, when no other leave is admissible to him/her, at the absolute discretion of the competent authority for a period not exceeding 24 months in the whole service. </li>
                                <li>The period of 24 months referred to above may be relaxed up to a maximum period of 48 months in the case of employees who desire to undertake doctoral researches which would be useful both for the institution where they are working and the employees concerned, provided such employees give an undertaking that on completion of the course, they would serve the Bank for a minimum of double the period of such leave availed by the Employee.</li>
                                <li>No pay and allowances are admissible during the period of extra-ordinary leave and the period spent on such leave shall not count for increments and also for qualifying service for purposes of gratuity benefits.</li>
                            </ul>


</div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
